{{Infobox person | name = François-Xavier Bellamy | image = Paris - La Manif pour Tous - 20141005 - 43.jpg | image_size = | caption = François-Xavier Bellamy in 2014 | birth_name = | birth_date = {{b-da|11 October 1985}} | birth_place = Paris, France | death_date = | death_place = | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = | residence = | nationality = | other_names = | known_for = | education = | alma mater = | employer = | occupation = Philosopher | title = | salary = | networth = | term = | predecessor = | successor = | party = | boards = | religion = | spouse = | children = | parents = | relatives = }} '''François-Xavier Bellamy''' (born 11 October 1985) is a French philosopher, award-winning author, high-school teacher and politician. He is a [[Mayor (France)#Deputy mayor|deputy mayor]] of [[Versailles]].
==Early life== François-Xavier Bellamy was born on 11 October 1985.<ref name="bnffrancoisxavierbellamy">{{cite web|title=François-Xavier Bellamy|url=http://data.bnf.fr/16918780/francois-xavier_bellamy/|website=Bibliothèque nationale de France|accessdate=February 22, 2017}}</ref><ref name="academieversaillesbio">{{cite web|title=BELLAMY François-Xavier|url=http://academiedeversailles.com/detail.php?categorie_id=1&scategorie_id=28&contact_id=1461|website=Académie des Sciences Morales, des Lettres et des Arts de Versailles|accessdate=February 22, 2017}}</ref>
Bellamy was educated at the Ecole Sainte-Marie des Bourdonnais, a private school in Versailles.<ref name="ecoleconference">{{cite web|title=Conférence|url=http://www.saintemarie-versailles.fr/rubriques/haut/agenda/conference-2|website=Ecole Sainte-Marie des Bourdonnais|accessdate=February 22, 2017}}</ref> After two-years [[Classe préparatoire aux grandes écoles|preparatory classes]] in the [[Lycée Henri-IV]], he got into the [[Ecole normale supérieure]], from which he graduated in 2005.<ref name="academieversaillesbio"/> He earned the [[agrégation]] in philosophy in 2008.<ref name="academieversaillesbio"/>
==Career== Bellamy taught philophy at the Lycée Sainte-Geneviève and the Lycée Notre-Dame de Grandchamp in Versailles in 2008.<ref name="academieversaillesbio"/> In 2009, he taught at the Lycée Auguste Renoir in [[Asnières-sur-Seine]], the Lycée Louis Bascan in [[Rambouillet]] and the Lycée hôtelier in [[Guyancourt]].<ref name="academieversaillesbio"/> Since 2011, he has been teaching philosophy and art history for the [[classe préparatoire aux grandes écoles|preparatory classes]] at the Lycée Blomet in Paris.<ref name="academieversaillesbio"/>
Bellamy is the author of three books. He won the Prix d'Aumale from the [[Académie française]] in 2014 for his first book, ''Les déshérités ou l'urgence de transmettre''.<ref name="leparisienleludeversaillesprimepour">{{cite news|title=L'élu de Versailles primé pour son livre " Les Déshérités "|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/versailles-78000/l-elu-de-versailles-prime-pour-son-livre-les-desherites-25-11-2015-5311585.php|accessdate=February 22, 2017|work=Le Parisien|date=November 25, 2015}}</ref> In this [[essay]], he analyses the failure of French educational system as the result of an ideology that refuses the transmission of culture, thus creating ''disinherited''. [[Jean-Jacques Rousseau]], [[René Descartes]] and [[Pierre Bourdieu]] would be the utmost representatives of this ideology.
He is the [[Mayor (France)#Deputy mayor|deputy mayor]] of [[Versailles]] for employment, youth and higher education.<ref name="academieversaillesbio"/> He was a candidate for the [[National Assembly (France)|National Assembly]] elections in 2017, invested by [[The Republicans (France)|The Republicans]], but he lost in the second round against the candidate of [[En Marche!]], with 48.9% vs 51.1% of the votes.<ref>http://elections.interieur.gouv.fr/legislatives-2017/078/07801.html</ref>
